Did you know that theaters had to close their doors over the last couple of years?! @studiomoviegrill Chisholm Trail was completed in Summer of 2020 but then had to actually close for over a year due to a lack of new movie releases. Lots of smaller theaters didn’t make it, but Studio Movie Grill is back in business as the anchor to the Shops at Chisholm trail (off of Chisholm Trail Parkway & McPherson).

I live in SW Fort Worth, just a quick drive from the theater. As a film fan, a pop culture enthusiast, and a mom who just needs a night out, I’m excited to have it nearby! With 12 screens, luxury recliner seating, a bar, good food, and that movie theater popcorn you just cant quit - consider grabbing some gift cards or tickets as gifts this year. Lots of staying home for the past couple years meant we were out of practice on traveling with kids!

Well, we got right back into the swing of it with a recent road trip. This wasn’t necessarily a monumental trip, but traveling with 3 young children makes everything a bigger deal. Over the trip, I took note of the things that helped keep everything smooth sailing, specifically with little ones in the back seat who go from 0 to 60 in a hot second.

So, instead of a traditional gift guide this year, I’ve put together the little things that helped us out most that you can still get fast for your own travel plans. Here’s hoping the real gift this year is peace, quiet, & sanity this holiday season.

Whipping up 5 dozen cookies to casually drop by my neighbors’ homes with a Christmas card - super chill and cool or super neurotic? The jury’s still out on that one! Regardless, I hope our neighbors are enjoying some (fantastic) lemon sugar cookies tonight! 💛

Recipe by @sarah_kieffer

As tempting as it would be to handle this myself, quickly, and get near perfect cookies - I want these little dudes involved!

Sure sure, the holiday traditions are nice, but this is really about the process imo. Baking helps us understand the importance of following directions, appreciating recipes and the science in our daily lives. It helps us work with our hands and process emotions through that work. In a way, baking grounds us.

But hey, I’ll get off my baking soapbox and say that sometimes you just need a safe environment to make mistakes. Cookies are perfect for littles as they’re learning how to handle expectations, communicate what they’re trying to achieve, but really, most importantly (again, impo) just being comfortable with mistakes. 

Here’s to baking with a purpose! 🍪

Hi. My name is Laura and I’m a Stanley Cup girlie.

In what feels like a tornado of never ending awfulness happening in our world, the topic of this 40oz cup still seems to be one of the hottest debates on social media. Admittedly, I jumped on in 2020 in support of the marketing technique Stanley used (the cup was brought into the marketplace exclusively through influencer marketing and as a whole, the strategy will be one that goes down in modern marketing history). Anywayyyy, I can’t explain it - but it works. I’ve gone from drinking a few glasses of water a day to easily +/- 100oz each day. Sure, I could have probably (ok definitely) already been prioritizing drinking water, but I hadn’t - and now I am. 

I can’t fix everything happening around us, and struggle with the amount of (really upsetting) headlines I’m bombarded with each day, I do know that I can take care of myself. I’m ok with being basic if it means I’m also hydrated. ✌️
I love being this guy’s valentine. 💕

Nothing to see here. 🔪 

Personal favs are @morbidpodcast, @myfavoritemurder, and @lpontheleft. Let me know in the comments what else I should be checking out.

A few small home-styling projects that have made a difference in how I enjoy the space. 

• I replaced the standard knobs on our entryway ikea shoe organizer with a couple gold statement cicadas and some smaller gold pulls.
• I was somehow able to find a watercolor print of my favorite pastry, the sfogliatelle (Lobster Tail). I framed it and hung it up in my kitchen.
• I had a seat cushion custom made for our bay window in a deep purple that matches our repurposed buffet. I get to sit here and read with my kids, watch storms blow in, and just relax with a cup of coffee.
• I had the script from one of my favorite Fleabag S2 monologues framed and on the wall in our bedroom.
• I need a new pot for my monstera but I finally worked with the moss pole to get this girl to fully stand up securely.
• I purchased some posters for Kyle’s office to create a very Kyle vibe. Not pictured are the new guitars we finally mounted on the walls which add a lot.

Anyway, I’m pretty proud of these little changes and the work put into making our home reflect who we are. If you need a reminder that you’re totally allowed to hang up a picture of your favorite pastry, just because - consider this exactly that! 💛

✨ march mattered ✨

At first, I watched this with shrugged shoulders and a big “eh.” Not a lot seemed to happen in March. But, the more I thought on it, the more I realized that’s just not true. A whole bunch of stuff happened. Actually - pretty big stuff! What I thought of as kind of an “uneventful” month was actually just a “smooth” month.

There’s a lot of big things going on in our world, and sometimes, it’s worth reminding ourselves that the small things we do for our loved ones matter. The things we do for our physical space matters. The things we do for ourselves matter.

Here’s to another month of all those little things making a big difference. 💛

In 2015, I saw @thesecretsisters open for Brandi Carlile at The Paramount Theatre in Seattle. Alongside @brandicarlile, they did an unplugged performance of Amazing Grace that is easily one of the most powerful spiritual moments I’ve had in my life. I was pregnant with James who would later get his middle name, Carlile, from this concert (and this pretty profound experience). 

At the time, I remember reading that his little baby ears were officially developed enough to begin hearing sounds outside of my body. I still tell him that the first thing he ever heard was folk music.

Last night, I was able to share all of this with Laura and Lydia and the impact they had on my life. Tell people you love that you love them. Tell them how much they mean to you. Tell them when they’re a part of significant moments in your life. Embrace that moment and any awkwardness that comes along with. It doesn’t need to be a big thing, it can just be a quick sentence in between sips of coffee. A huge thank you to @fwcrowdedtable for putting on an event that allowed me to do just that in a very big way. 💖

A lil’ ode to Fort Worth. 🫶

Our not-so-little city has garnered some heavy national attention over the past couple of days. The reason behind that attention is unfortunate (understatement) but what I really want to talk about is the response.

Seeing people protecting the Fort Worth LGBTQIA+ community is beautiful. Seeing folks make connections between the discriminatory business practices and that of Mercy Culture’s continued presence is incredible. People who, even just a year ago would say “that’s not really something I get involved in” are now standing up, ready to help keep our LGBTQIA+ loved ones safe. If you’re someone who took a huge step this week - to share your thoughts, repost, or simply remind people of where you stand - I see you and I’m proud of you.

When I started doing this little side gig, I wanted it to be about my voice - not as a mom, as a wife, not my faith identity, or even the city I live in. Social media changes and our lives change, but I will always want my platforms to reflect my voice. My voice will always be affirming of the LGBTQIA+ community. My voice will always correct ableism and fatphobia when it weeds in. My voice will always call out white supremacy. I will use my breath to speak up for those that can’t breathe.

However big or teenie tiny that looks for you, I encourage you to do the same. Use your voice.💖

“I love you but I don’t agree with that lifestyle.”

That was my answer. No really. I genuinely thought I was being there for my friends with that. I thought I was communicating that I loved them, while also being true to the God I was taught to believe in. I really believed I had all the bases covered and totally nailed it.

I was wrong. ✨So, so wrong.✨
Over the years, I’ve since reconnected and made a point to apologize for that specific hurt I put on my LGBTQIA+ friends who chose me as a safe person to come out to. It took a long time, and I still fight back shame in the harm I’ve been complicit in, but I’m here now.

It’s because of that same faith that I’m called to believe there is hope for others, too. If you’re looking at the first line of this as a banger of a response to any queer person, for any reason, in any situation - I want you to know I’m here for you. Kyle too, actually. My DM’s are always open, our schedule is flexible. We make time for these conversations. They’re worth it.

Happy Pride, Fort Worth! Thank you for coming out. ❤️🧡💛💚💙💜

We celebrated the grand opening of the Vivian J. Lincoln Library, named after the first female African-American principal in Crowley ISD. ⁠While we often hop all over the city, this library is the closest to our home and within our own Council District (6). Libraries are so important, providing resources and materials that might not be available or affordable. The reality is that not everyone can afford a computer, internet access, books, or the many other resources libraries provide. Right now with little ones and these heat waves, not everyone even even has a cool place to play with their children. Our district’s City Council Representative, @jaredwilliamstx, took a moment to meet the boys and talk to them about their new library. Our oldest has been with us each time we cast our vote for him and as we’ve been introducing politics to our kids through our local elections, Jared has been an example of someone they can look up to. You’ll see us here a lot, taking advantage of their activity room (with a similar feel to the Museum of Science rooms if you’re familiar).

We already love our local library! Next time you need an indoor activity (for kids or adults), stop by and fall in love with it yourself!

Part of understanding (reminder that the word “deconstructing” is not a buzz word but synonymous for understanding) my continued belief and faith in Christian theology means that lately I’m able to lean into it in a way I never felt free to.

BRB, I’m in my Barbie world! Jk I’m here in reality and quickly breaking down whether you should or shouldn’t bring your kids to see the new Barbie movie.

The movie is rated PG-13 for “suggestive references” and “brief language,” and while normally in agreement with most MPAA ratings, I’d actually say that this one depends on the age. It’s definitely not toddler friendly, so just bc you have a child at home playing with barbies, that doesn’t mean it’s a go.

Have you ever had a moment where you looked at a little girl and kind of broke a little inside for them, knowing she’s beginning to experience the world in a way that’s unfair or sexist? If you’ve had that moment, I would say it’s probably ok. If anything, I could see it being a great conversation starter with younger (ie preteen, almost preteen) girls on what being a woman is or even what being a safe person looks like in our culture (the real world vs. barbie world). There’s some solid mom and angsty-daughter bonding that’s personally, I felt was really valuable seeing represented on screen (in a way that’s not cheesy).

That being said, there are a lot of jokes around sex and attraction, so if that’s not something you’ve already discussed together, there may be some discomfort. Unfortunately, I think a lot of kids are already familiar with both the concept and being sexualized (even if they don’t realize it). 

It’s a total girl’s girl film and made me feel seen in ways I wasn’t expecting. The message is a great one and the humor is, too.

It gets a ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ from me, but I’ll let you make the call on who you attend with.
#barbiemovie #barbie

I’m not much of a yoga girlie but I gave it my all today during the Yoga & Strings class at @artsfortworth!

There are a whole lotta reasons to feel a disconnect from our body. I’m not sure I can make it a full day without an experience of internalized fatphobia affecting it in some way. 🫐 what you need:
1 box of @kodiakcakes Protein-Packed Muffin Mix (I went with blueberry)
3 eggs
3/4 cup milk (or water)
1 glug of vanilla extract
1 cup shredded zucchini (roughly 1 medium)
2 tbsp melted butter, cooled (can sub with oil)
1 cup (frozen or fresh) blueberries - reserve 1/4-1/2 for sprinkling on top

🫐 what you do:
mix milk, eggs, vanilla, butter until combined. After shredding/grating zucchini, squeeze out as much liquid as possible. Fold in zucchini and box mix. Lightly fold in the blueberries. Pour into greased 9x13 pan. Grab those blueberries that were set aside and sprinkle them on top. Bake at 350F for 20min. 

Sit back and watch them double-fist these muffins while insisting they’ll never eat vegetables. But be careful with this step. You’ve got to be chill. Kids can sense your investment.

Look at these two kids getting out and some alone time together! When I heard Hotel Drover was having a spooky themed, Backyard Unplugged session, I knew this was the time to stop by. That’s right - it was actually my first time at Drover. (cue the gasp.)

We really thought we could have a loosey-goosey, nonchalant attitude toward date nights but eventually realized that it wasn’t working. In an attempt to be the cool, laid back couple, we were actually missing out on both intentional time together and opportunities to explore our city.

So, we started with dinner at @97westkitchenbar. I had a Bluebonnet, the Drover version of a lemon drop. It was a dream with their fried green tomatoes (which had been marinated in sweet tea, because of course). After dinner, we went out back and enjoyed live music by @jonathanarthurmusic and some spooky cocktails from The Pour Horse. With the mood set, cozy sweater, a fire pit, and some fantastic drinks - it made for a kind of beautiful evening together. Honestly, for being in the proximity of so many people, the whole evening felt very intimate. The Backyard experience was exactly what we needed. Thanks @hoteldrover and @97westkitchenbar for hosting us and giving us a night to remember.

Grab your sweaters and head to The Backyard at Hotel Drover for your next date night. Follow along at @hoteldrover to keep up with what events are around the corner, so you can carve out time for your own night-out together. 🖤

I'm taking my London Fog game to the next level this holiday season.

This my go-to warm drink, so why not create a jazzy version of it for the holidays. By "jazzy" I definitely mean alcoholic, but that's one of the best parts about this drink in particular - the mocktail version is still a bonafide hit. 

What you'll need:
• Earl Grey
• Hawaiian Shaved Ice Vanilla Syrup 
• Cotton Candy Express Pink Vanilla Sugar 
• Heavy Cream
*Optional: 2oz Bourbon of your choice

What you'll do:
•Steep that tea as long as you want. This is your drink, so you do you, baby.
I used a traditional Irish Coffee mug. If you use glass, make sure to preheat your glass. Swish a little hot water around to temper that glass, so it'll be ready for your drink.
If you're spiking, go ahead and add the 2oz Bourbon. 
•Add a splash of the Hawaiian Shaved Ice Vanilla Syrup (let your heart measure).
• Add 1/2 cup (depending on how many drinks you’re making) heavy cream to a small bowl. Add a couple teaspoons of the Cotton Candy Express Sugar in Pink Vanilla. This will add flavor and color. Whip that cream, adding more sugar if necessary. Now, top the mug off with the pink vanilla cream you've created and dust on some extra sugar.
• Enjoy!

If you're looking for a last minute stunner for under the tree, shop through the link in my bio. Don't sleep on a great way to jazz up your everyday or holiday drinks. #HSIHolidayDrinks #HSIPartner #ad

We moved to Fort Worth already fans of coffee shop culture. Knowing pretty much no one for the first year(ish) had us regularly visiting coffee shops all around the city to find our fit and learn about our new home.

Over time, I found myself running into @katonaleash and over and over seeing how she inspired others. As a woman within the white, evangelical world - it kind of blew my mind to see a woman make big things happen but still be one of the kindest people I had ever met.

You can see her love of people and Fort Worth reflected in Cherry Coffee and those who spend time there. From students, to remote workers, friends catching up, and families with young children - Cherry reflects the kind of belonging we all want and deep down, ✨need✨ in a community.

When the opportunity to bring Novel Roasters to Fort Worth, she took it. Roasted here in Fort Worth, the @novelcoffeeroasters site went live this week and ships nationally.

Since getting to know Katherine, I’m still blown away by her and honored to call her a friend. I’m ridiculously proud of her and when I suggest you pick up some coffee for last minute stocking stuffers - I mean it. I believe in her hope to bring underrepresented coffee roasters (ie women and POC) into the spotlight and I believe in her.

You can pick up last minute, local gifts at:
📍 @cherrycoffeefw
1121 W Magnolia Ave.

📍 @novelcoffeeroasters
2800 Shamrock Ave #124

Follow along. There’s a lot coming in 2024. ☕️
